<br>
If i were to design a computer for space travel, i would do it like this.  start with a flat panel monitor, add an internal motherboard and chip, a few USB connections, large (capacity wise, not physical size) internal hard drive, and an internal dvd burner drive.  This would be a few inches thick, and could have a USB mouse, and keyboard.  With the DVD burner, you could use the 9.7 gb discs as your portable hard drive.  This would all weigh a good 10 pounds or so, maybe 20.  You would have all the capabilities of your PC, with no tower, less weight, and less pure bulk. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 651<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/5/03 12:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: space colonists</span><hr size=1> If we were to go to another star system using today's technology the price of a DVD player would be irrelevant if something catastrophic happens to it enroute.  The colonists could have all the information in the world on how to build power plants or repair broken computers but that doesn't mean they'll be able to physically procure the resources they need to do those things.  Heck, I could get a good set of plans for building a Saturn V rocket but I'd be hardpressed to actually build it since I, like a small group of colonists, couldn't hope to make the factories and do the mining that would be required to pull it off.  You need a lot of people and a lot of infrastruc